[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]12
[normal]              
[normal]The winter season started on 1
[normal] October
[normal] and as of that date w
[normal]e are
[normal] ready 
[normal]           
[normal]to treat the network with plant and materials 
[normal]standing by. 
[normal]Our salt stock levels 
[normal]           
[normal]have been revised in accordance with national guidance and we now have a 
[normal]           
[normal]contracted minimum stock level, sufficient to treat the network 90 times, whic
[normal]h 
[normal]           
[normal]equates to a minimum stock of s
[normal]ome 10,000 tonnes. 
[normal]Current stock levels 
[normal]           
[normal]stand at approximately 14,400 tonnes, giving an operational buffer of 4,400 
[normal]           
[normal]tonnes.  Stock replenishment will be undertaken during the season so as
[normal] to 
[normal]         
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]maintain an operational buffer and only in c
[normal]ontinual severe conditions will
[normal]         
[normal] 
[normal] there 
[normal]be a risk of stock levels falling below the minimum 10,000 tonne 
[normal]          
[normal] 
[normal]requirement. 
[normal]Salt usage through the winter will obviously depend on th
[normal]e 
[normal]         
[normal] 
[normal] conditions that 
[normal]ultimately develop
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.13
[normal]   
[normal]As risk mitigation against in season shortage of salt from suppliers, TfL has 
[normal]          
[normal]established a pan-London Reserve Salt Stock of 27,000t, held at Dagenham, 
[normal]          
[normal]available to ourselves and the boroughs. This is to be used 
[normal]as a last resort
[normal]          
[normal]after all supply chain or options for mutual aid between neighbouring 
[normal]          
[normal]authorities have been exhausted. With prudent use that should be sufficient to 
[normal]        
[normal]  
[normal]treat London’s key ‘resilience’ routes for a period of about two weeks.
