[normal]3.   [bold]London Underground and TfL’s rail network [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Weather forecasting
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]TfL’s rail network 
[normal]and LU
[normal] use the Met Office to predict levels of snowfall and ice accumulation
[normal] as well as our own 
[normal]network
[normal]-wide
[normal] rail temperature equipment. To complement this, MeteoGroup provide a forecast rail icing risk at over 20 locations over the LU network (the locations eac
[normal]h have instrumented sets of rail for temperature and moisture, which give real time data). 
[normal]London 
[normal]R
[normal]ail
[normal] collects local temperature informa
[normal]tion from defined cold spot location
[normal]s. This information 
[normal]triggers the
[normal] response plans
[normal] as appropriate
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Operational proces
[normal]ses
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]LU and L
[normal]ondon 
[normal]R
[normal]ail
[normal] work on five day readiness proce
[normal]ss
[normal] 
[normal]for a predicted forecast of snow and a similar three day readiness process for ice, both of 
[normal]which aim to minimise the impact of the forecasted weather.  All affected rail routes are 
[normal]pre-emptively treated in the hour
[normal]s leading up to 
[normal]and then during 
[normal]winter
[normal] weather conditions
[normal] in accordance with pre-determined plans
[normal]. Where routes 
[normal]are affected
[normal], contingency plans are in place to divert customers and curtail rail services to concentrate on pr
[normal]iority locations. 
